## I. INTRODUCTION

Compute Express Link (CXL) has emerged as the dominant interconnect standard for memory disaggregation in hyperscale and AI data-centres. CXL 2.0 introduced pooled memory and fabric switching; CXL 3.0 extended this to multi-level fabrics and peer-to-peer coherence; CXL 4.0 further refined Dynamic Capacity Devices (DCD), Port-Based Routing (PBR), and the Fabric Manager (FM) API that orchestrates all of these components.

The FM API is the control plane for every multi-tenant CXL fabric. It is the sole mechanism through which memory regions are allocated across tenants, physical ports are enabled or disabled, and virtual PCI-to-PCI bridges (vPPBs) are bound to logical devices. Despite its privileged position, the FM API has received almost no security scrutiny: prior CXL security research has focused on side-channel leakage in coherency traffic, memory encryption, and SPDM key exchange at device bring-up. The FM control plane—the entity that decides which tenant owns which memory—has been assumed trusted.

**This assumption is wrong.**

We make the following contributions:

1. We perform a systematic security audit of the CXL FM API command set—spanning physical port management, vPPB management, MLD management, DCD management, and switch/tunnel management—and identify five normative specification gaps (GAP-1 through GAP-5) that, collectively, leave FM command authentication undefined by the CXL standard. *(Note: specific opcode values pending final verification against the authoritative CXL specification text — see Section X.)*
2. We demonstrate that the MCTP transport used by FM API allows any MCTP-capable process with bus access to issue FM commands directly to a CXL switch, bypassing the FM software daemon entirely.
3. We construct four end-to-end attacks (ATK-1 through ATK-4) that exploit these gaps to achieve cross-tenant memory hijacking, denial-of-service, capacity starvation, and command injection.
4. We propose a four-layer defence architecture, each with both a hardware-backed and a software-only deployment variant, and a concrete two-phase standardisation roadmap for the CXL Consortium.

The remainder of the paper is organised as follows. Section II provides CXL and FM API background. Section III analyses the five normative gaps. Section IV defines the threat model. Section V presents the four attacks, with message-sequence diagrams for each. Section VI describes evaluation methodology. Section VII proposes defences, software-only variants, and the standardisation roadmap. Section VIII surveys related work. Section IX concludes. Section X lists open verification items.

