## II. BACKGROUND

### A. CXL Architecture Overview

CXL is a cache-coherent, PCIe-physical-layer interconnect that supports three device types: Type-1 (cache-only), Type-2 (cache + memory), and Type-3 (memory-only). CXL 2.0 introduced pooled Type-3 devices accessible by multiple hosts through a CXL fabric switch. CXL 3.0 extended this to multi-level fabrics with port-based routing (PBR) replacing the earlier hierarchical binding (HBR). CXL 4.0 refined DCD extents, fabric-level telemetry, and the Fabric Manager API. CXL's Multi-Logical Device (MLD) and Virtual CXL Switch (VCS) mechanisms allow multiple tenants to share a single physical port, each bound to a distinct Logical Device (LD) via the switch's virtual switching layer — so a fabric's tenant count is not bounded by its physical port count.

