### B. Fabric Manager and FM API

The Fabric Manager is a software entity (typically a daemon running on a baseboard management controller or service processor) responsible for configuring the CXL fabric. It communicates with CXL switches and devices using the FM API, a set of management commands transported over the Management Component Transport Protocol (MCTP) [2].

The FM API defines commands for physical port management, vPPB management, Multi-Logical Device (MLD) management, Dynamic Capacity (DCD) management, and switch/tunnel management. *(Specific opcode ranges are pending verification against the authoritative spec text — see Section X.)*

### C. MCTP Transport and Addressing

Components that implement an MCTP-based Component Command Interface (CCI) are assigned a unique Endpoint ID (EID) by the MCTP bus owner via the Set Endpoint ID control command [2]. FM API messages to such components are MCTP messages with a defined CXL FM API message type. Critically, MCTP itself provides no authentication: any process with access to the MCTP bus (SMBus, PCIe VDM, or a Unix-domain-socket abstraction) can send well-formed FM API payloads to any assigned CXL EID. *(The specific message-type value is pending verification against DSP0239 — see Section X.)*

### D. SPDM Authentication in CXL

CXL 2.0 and later mandate that devices support Security Protocol and Data Model (SPDM) [3] for device identity verification. SPDM provides challenge-response authentication via its CHALLENGE/CHALLENGE_AUTH exchange: the requester sends a random nonce, and the device returns that nonce signed with its private key, proving possession of the certificate's corresponding key without proving anything about the device's current firmware integrity. However, the CXL Consortium FAQ states that SPDM usage for FM "can be employed," not that it "shall" be employed [11]. This permissive language is the root cause of GAP-2. *(We were unable to locate equivalent normative SHALL/CAN language directly in the base specification text reviewed; this claim is attributed to the Consortium FAQ pending further verification — see Section X.)*

### E. Dynamic Capacity Devices

A DCD exposes one or more DC Regions from which the FM allocates extents to hosts using DCD_ADD_CAPACITY and DCD_RELEASE_CAPACITY commands. The host receives a Dynamic Capacity Event notification on extent state transitions, delivered via the device's standard interrupt mechanism. There is no cryptographic binding between the extent grant recorded by the FM and the state held in device hardware—this is GAP-4.

