## V. ATTACK DESIGN

### A. ATK-1: vPPB-Rebind (Cross-Tenant Memory Hijacking)

**Objective**: Redirect a vPPB currently bound to Tenant A's memory region to an attacker-controlled logical device, gaining read/write access to Tenant A's physical memory.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker
    participant Switch as CXL Switch (FM API)
    participant Victim as Tenant A's Logical Device

    Note over Attacker,Switch: No authentication required (GAP-1, GAP-2)
    Attacker->>Switch: UNBIND_VPPB(victim's vPPB)
    Switch->>Victim: Detach binding
    Switch-->>Attacker: UNBIND_RESPONSE
    Attacker->>Switch: BIND_VPPB(same vPPB, Attacker's LD)
    Switch->>Victim: Rebind vPPB to attacker's LD
    Switch-->>Attacker: BIND_RESPONSE
    Attacker->>Attacker: Enumerate new LD via PCIe discovery
    Note over Attacker,Victim: Attacker now has CXL.mem access<br/>to victim's physical memory.<br/>FM software table diverges from<br/>hardware state (GAP-3).
```
**Figure 3**: ATK-1 (vPPB-Rebind) Message Sequence

**Mechanism**: Because the switch hardware processes commands in arrival order and no authentication is required (GAP-1, GAP-2), the rebind succeeds unconditionally. The FM software's routing table now diverges from the actual hardware state (GAP-3), since the FM was never consulted.

### B. ATK-2: PortDoS (Shared Physical Port Denial-of-Service)

**Objective**: Disable a shared upstream switch port, severing connectivity for all tenants sharing that port.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker
    participant Switch as CXL Switch (FM API)
    participant Victims as All Tenants on Shared Port

    Attacker->>Switch: Enumerate ports (port-state query)
    Switch-->>Attacker: Port list + states
    Note over Attacker,Switch: No token required (GAP-1)
    Attacker->>Switch: SET_PHY_PORT_STATE(victim port, DISABLED)
    Switch->>Victims: Port physically disabled
    Switch-->>Attacker: ACK
    Note over Victims: All devices on this port disconnected
```
**Figure 4**: ATK-2 (PortDoS) Message Sequence

**Mechanism**: Because physical port control requires no token (GAP-1), and port IDs are enumerable, this requires a single MCTP message.

### C. ATK-3: DCDrain (Dynamic Capacity Starvation)

**Objective**: Silently revoke memory extents allocated to a live tenant workload, causing silent data loss or OOM in an LLM serving process.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker
    participant DCD as DCD Device EID
    participant Victim as Victim Tenant Host

    Note over Attacker,DCD: Direct MCTP access bypasses<br/>the legitimate FM entirely (GAP-4)
    Attacker->>DCD: DCD_RELEASE_CAPACITY(victim's extent)
    DCD->>DCD: Mark extent FREE
    Note over Victim: No Dynamic Capacity Event sent —<br/>victim is unaware of the release.<br/>Victim's page tables still point<br/>to the reclaimed memory.
    Attacker->>DCD: DCD_ADD_CAPACITY(same extent, Attacker)
    DCD-->>Attacker: Extent granted
    Attacker->>Attacker: Read residual victim memory
```

**Figure 5**: ATK-3 (DCDrain) Message Sequence

**Mechanism**: Exploiting GAP-4, the attacker sends a fabricated DCD_RELEASE_CAPACITY directly to the DCD device EID, specifying extents currently owned by the victim tenant. The victim host does not receive an event notification because the FM was not involved.

This attack is particularly damaging for AI inference workloads: releasing extents backing an LLM's KV-cache can silently corrupt or evict cached state without triggering any OS-level fault.

### D. ATK-4: TunnelSpoof (Fabric Manager Identity Spoofing)

**Objective**: Inject arbitrary FM API commands to a Type-3 device behind a switch by exploiting GAP-5's unauthenticated tunnel forwarding.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker
    participant OuterSwitch as Outer CXL Switch
    participant InnerDevice as Downstream Type-3 Device

    Attacker->>OuterSwitch: TUNNEL_MANAGEMENT_COMMAND<br/>(outer EID = switch)
    Note over OuterSwitch: Strips outer header.<br/>No check on inner command's<br/>origin or authorisation (GAP-5)
    OuterSwitch->>InnerDevice: Forwarded inner FM API command
    InnerDevice->>InnerDevice: Executes command as if from legitimate FM
    InnerDevice-->>OuterSwitch: Response
    OuterSwitch-->>Attacker: TUNNEL_RESPONSE
    Note over InnerDevice: Device cannot distinguish a<br/>tunnelled attacker command from<br/>one issued by the real FM.
```

**Figure 6**: ATK-4 (TunnelSpoof) Message Sequence

**Mechanism**: The attacker crafts a TUNNEL_MANAGEMENT_COMMAND with the outer EID set to the switch's EID and the inner payload containing any desired FM API command targeting the victim device. The switch strips the outer header and forwards the inner command without verifying its origin.

